entry.title: [DevTools] Add PostScript name to font usage data
entry.content:
Previously, we only send font family name through CDP, which in some

cases [1] is not enough. In this CL, we send an additional name,

PostScript name, as well, to better distinguish between different

fonts with the same family name.



Since the original data structure storing font data is a HashCountedSet with a key of {isCustomFont, family_name}, and the glyph count as value, we also have to change the data structure to a HashMap with the similar key {isCustomFont, postscript_name (which is more strict)}, and the value as {glyph_count, family_name}.

user can choose it again. This history is kept track of via a list of

token strings saved in prefs.

front of the history list and keep everything else in relatively the

same order. Example:

original history: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6

entry.title: Fix resource request related UMA
entry.content:
The following UMAs were introduced by https://crrev.com/c/3613548:

Blink.Loading.CodeCacheArrivalAtRenderer

Blink.Loading.CachedResponseArrivalAtRenderer

But they are not recorded after https://crrev.com/c/4910676 which

removed the logic of setting `code_cache_arrival_time_`.

We are not monitoring them anymore so this CL removes them.



This CL also changes following UMAs more precisely record the IPC delay

by ignoring frozen requests and by recording the time when the

renderer receives the IPC in MojoURLLoaderClient, and adds "2" suffix.

Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay -> StartDelay2

Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay -> ResponseDelay2

Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay -> RedirectDelay

Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay -> CompletionDelay2



Also this CL changes ResourceRequestSender to use the time when the

renderer receives the IPC in MojoURLLoaderClient instead of the time

recorded in ResourceRequestSender for converting the renderer side

timing information from the network service side timing information.

(Technically this can change Resource Timing information. But this

happens only when the page was frozen on pre-Vista Windows.)



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.Loading.CodeCacheArrivalAtRenderer]=No used.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.Loading.CachedResponseArrivalAtRenderer]=Not used.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay2.

entry.title: Disable ALLOW_MISALIGNED in third_party/unrar
entry.content:
This fixes a host of UBSan errors, such as this one:

https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/inv/build-8764440332290274033/test-results?q=FileAnalyzerTest.RarAnalysisResultMetric&sortby=&groupby=



Although the underlying architecture may allow unaligned access, C and

C++ themselves do not allow this. Rather, unaligned loads should be

written with either memcpy, or by endian-agnostic reassembling of values

with shifts and ORs. Modern compilers recognize these patterns and

generate the unaligned load anyway.



There are a couple places where, depending on inlining, the compiler may

not be able to generate the same code. E.g. this function requires the

compiler know that `dest` cannot alias `arg1` or `arg2`.

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/unrar/src/rijndael.cpp;drc=b86eab797178b986437ab3db265cceabf0b0496a;l=22



(It would be possible to write that in a way that is both

well-defined and encourages the compiler to load 4 bytes at a time.

Though we'd actually want it to load 16 bytes at a time with SIMD

instructions.)



But I assume unrar is not a hot path for us. If it were, we should

replace that file with calls to BoringSSL anyway, which has actually

optimized implementations. (Rijndael is the original name of AES.)

entry.title: Remove alignment requirements on source_image_ in BrowserThemePack
entry.content:
BrowserThemePack aliases various types into an underlying buffer. A

priori, this is not safe because types must be aligned, but all the

types are wrapped in `#pragma pack` to remove their alignment

requirements.



Strictly speaking, this is still not allowed in C++ due to strict

aliasing requirements, but Chromium disables strict aliasing and

attempting to fix this would require rewriting a lot of code.



However, `source_images_` just has type `int`, and `#pragma pack` only

applies to types defined in the region of code. As a result,

`source_images_` still has the usual alignment requirements of `int`.

UBSan flagged a violation of this here:



https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/inv/build-8764440332290274033/test-results?q=BrowserThemePackTest.HiDpiThemeTest&sortby=&groupby=



To avoid this problem, wrap the int in a struct. `#pragma pack` then

applies and we remove the alignment requirement.

entry.title: [window-splitting] Fix splitting on extended displays.
entry.content:
There were two issues that caused the bug:



1) When repositioning the windows on drag completion, the bounds were

set using `SetBounds()`, which expected values in root window

coordinates, but the values passed in were in screen coordinates. This

was changed to use `SetBoundsInScreen()`.



2) When dragging a window across different displays, the root window

changes between the call to `Drag()` and `CompleteDrag()`, which changes

the frame of reference of "parent" coordinates. The code was storing the

last drag location in parent coordinates between the two calls, so when

the value was converted back to screen coordinates later, it resulted in

a different screen location. The fix was to store the last drag location

in screen coordinates instead.



Added tests to exercise both conditions above.

entry.title: Enable echo cancellation for AAudio input
entry.content:
This CL adds Echo Cancellation support for AAudio inputs, by properly

setting the input preset on the stream.



We use AAUDIO_INPUT_PRESET_VOICE_COMMUNICATION when the

AudioParameters::ECHO_CANCELLER effect bit is set, and

AAUDIO_INPUT_PRESET_CAMCORDER in all other cases.



We choose the *CAMCORDER preset instead of the default preset of

*VOICE_RECOGNITION for two reasons:

- We use *CAMCORDER with OpenSL ES, and we are keeping parity.

- *CAMCORDER uses a wider signal band than *VOICE_RECOGNITION.



We do not use AAUDIO_INPUT_PRESET_UNPROCESSED, because the lack of

automatic gain control results in quiet, sometimes silent, streams.



See https://crbug.com/1501352#c39 for a comparison of the different

presets.

entry.title: Remove `will_cause_resize` from WebContents::ExitFullscreen()
entry.content:
This CL fixes a regression on Mac that if a web page enters the tab

fullscreen mode and then exits fullscreen by system controls (keyboard

shortcuts or window control buttons), the page becomes

fullscreen-in-tab. This issue was caused by the browser not sending

a resize message to the renderer after browser has exited fullscreen.

Specifically, the resize message isn't sent because the browser

is told that there will by another resize event and skips this message

when `will_cause_resize` is True.



This issue can be solved by removing the `will_cause_resize` parameter

from WebContents::ExitFullscreen() so that a resize message is sent

every time this function is called to exit fullscreen.



The `will_cause_resize` flag was initially added to restore the

scroll position when toggling fullscreen mode crrev.com/1488653002

However, the scroll restoration was later removed because of its

complexity by crrev.com/c/1195714 and this flag wasn't cleaned up

at that time.



There are several places where a True value is passed to

`will_cause_resize` i.e. exit fullscreen when showing a printer pop

up dialog. These use cases shouldn't be affected by having another

page resize.

intersection update but didn't invalidate cached rects of the target.

entry.title: Refactor blink signal to autofill on form related changes
entry.content:
Currently blink sends a signal to Autofill about form related elements

being added/removed in a single signal. There exist several problems

with the current mechanism:



-Blink calls it when a ListedElement is reassociated to another form,

which is neither an add nor a remove operation.

-The type of operation that fired the signal is lost (add/remove)

-The actual element affected is lost on the way to AutofillAgent.



This CL:

-Adds an enum WebFormRelatedChange to identify the actual type of change

that happened. This will be used on Autofill side because not all change

types will be handled the same way.



-Adds a `kReassociate` value to distinguish reassociation from additions

and removals.



-Renames the function DidAddOrRemoveFormRelatedElement to

DidChangeFormRelatedElementDynamically to reflect that this signal is

not limited to additions and removals (will later also be used for

elements becoming hidden).



-Passes the element changed as a parameter of the signal all the way to

AutofillAgent. This can be used to deduce the nature of the element.

(Form vs Field) and for submission tracking purposes.
